#
# WHAT IS go.uber.org/zap AND WHY IS IT THE 52ND GO CLI LIBRARY?
#
# zap (https://github.com/uber-go/zap, 24500+ stars) is **Uber
# Engineering's "blazing fast, structured, leveled logging in
# Go"** — the Go logger optimized for high-throughput production
# services where logging hot-paths represent measurable CPU +
# allocation overhead.  zap was created at Uber to address the
# performance problems of sirupsen/logrus + golang/glog +
# golang/log when used in services handling millions of
# requests/second.
#
# zap's distinguishing characteristics:
#
#   1. TYPED-FIELD API AVOIDS REFLECTION — Where logrus uses
#      `log.WithFields(logrus.Fields{"key": value})` (reflection
#      on the map, allocations per field), zap uses TYPED CTOR
#      FUNCTIONS for fields:
#
#          import "go.uber.org/zap"
#
#          logger, _ := zap.NewProduction()
#          defer logger.Sync()
#
#          logger.Info("user logged in",
#              zap.String("username", username),
#              zap.Int("user_id", userID),
#              zap.Duration("login_duration", elapsed),
#              zap.Time("login_time", time.Now()),
#              zap.Bool("first_login", isFirst),
#              zap.Error(err),
#          )
#
#      Every typed function (zap.String/Int/Float64/Bool/
#      Duration/Time/Error/Any/...) avoids reflection by knowing
#      the field type at compile time.  Compare:
#         * logrus: log.WithFields(map[string]interface{}{...})
#                    — reflection + map allocations
#         * zerolog: log.Info().Str("k", v).Int("n", x).Msg(...)
#                     — chainable, similar typed approach
#         * stdlib slog (Go 1.21+): slog.Info("msg", "key", value)
#                                    — variadic keyvalues, runtime
#                                      type assertions
#         * zap: zap.String/Int/Float/... ctor functions
#      FIRST documented Go logger with typed-field-ctor API
#      avoiding reflection.
#
#   2. SUGARED LOGGER FOR ERGONOMICS — When typed-field API
#      ceremony is too much, zap offers SugaredLogger with
#      printf-style ergonomics at ~2x the cost (still faster
#      than logrus):
#
#          sugar := logger.Sugar()
#          sugar.Infof("user %s logged in at %v", username, time.Now())
#          sugar.Infow("user logged in",
#              "username", username,
#              "user_id", userID,
#              "elapsed", elapsed,
#          )
#
#      `Infof` is printf-style; `Infow` is structured with
#      key-value variadic args.  Compare:
#         * logrus: log.Info(...) is printf-style by default
#         * zerolog: requires chain-end .Msgf(...)
#         * zap: TWO APIs (Logger for performance + Sugared for
#                 ergonomics) in one library
#      FIRST documented Go logger with dual-tier API (typed +
#      sugared) for performance/ergonomics tradeoff.
#
#   3. JSON + CONSOLE + CUSTOM ENCODER ARCHITECTURE — zap's
#      output is governed by an Encoder + Core architecture:
#
#          // JSON encoder: production-ready structured logs
#          config := zap.NewProductionConfig()
#          logger, _ := config.Build()
#          // Outputs: {"level":"info","ts":1234567890.123,"caller":"...","msg":"...","user":"alice"}
#
#          // Console encoder: human-readable colored
#          config := zap.NewDevelopmentConfig()
#          logger, _ := config.Build()
#          // Outputs: 2024-01-01T12:00:00.000Z  INFO  user="alice"   message
#
#          // Custom encoder via zapcore.EncoderConfig
#          encoderConfig := zapcore.EncoderConfig{
#              TimeKey:        "ts",
#              LevelKey:       "level",
#              NameKey:        "logger",
#              MessageKey:     "msg",
#              StacktraceKey:  "stacktrace",
#              EncodeLevel:    zapcore.CapitalLevelEncoder,
#              EncodeTime:     zapcore.ISO8601TimeEncoder,
#              EncodeDuration: zapcore.MillisDurationEncoder,
#              EncodeCaller:   zapcore.ShortCallerEncoder,
#          }
#
#      Compare:
#         * logrus: text or JSON formatter
#         * zerolog: JSON only
#         * stdlib slog: text or JSON via Handler
#         * zap: JSON + Console + custom encoders + atomic level
#                 changes at runtime
#      FIRST documented Go logger with encoder + core
#      decomposition architecture.
#
#   4. ZERO-ALLOC DESIGN VIA OBJECT POOLING — zap pools its
#      buffer.Buffer + zapcore.Entry + zapcore.Field objects
#      via sync.Pool.  In steady-state operation, logging at
#      INFO level executes with ZERO ALLOCATIONS in the hot
#      path.  Benchmark from zap's own README:
#         * zap (typed):     ~200ns/op,  0 alloc/op
#         * zap (sugared):   ~600ns/op,  1 alloc/op
#         * zerolog:         ~150ns/op,  0 alloc/op (similar)
#         * stdlib slog:    ~1100ns/op,  4 alloc/op
#         * logrus:         ~5000ns/op, 25 alloc/op
#         * apex/log:       ~6000ns/op, 30 alloc/op
#      Compare every other documented Go logger — only zerolog
#      matches zap's zero-alloc design.  FIRST documented Go
#      logger with sync.Pool-based zero-alloc hot-path.
#
#   5. UBER-ECOSYSTEM PROVENANCE + KUBERNETES ADOPTION —
#      zap was created at Uber Engineering to solve real
#      hot-path logging overhead in Uber's production Go
#      services.  Major users:
#         * Uber's entire Go service ecosystem
#         * Kubernetes ecosystem: kubebuilder, operator-sdk,
#           controller-runtime (uses zap as default via logr
#           bridge)
#         * CockroachDB
#         * TiKV-go-client (TiDB's KV layer)
#         * Etcd v3.5+ (replaced its custom logger with zap)
#         * VMware Tanzu projects
#         * gRPC-Go's logging interfaces
#         * Many cloud-native CNCF projects
#      Compare every other documented Go logger — only logrus
#      has comparable adoption breadth, but zap is the
#      modern default for performance-sensitive services.
#      FIRST documented Go logger with Kubernetes-ecosystem
#      default-status provenance.
#
# zap's relationship to other documented Go libraries:
#
#   * Like fatih/color (Axis 4) — both produce styled
#                                  terminal output
#   * Unlike fatih/color — zap is structured-logging-focused;
#                           fatih/color is presentation-coloring
#   * Like consola (R576 TS-Node) — both are unified loggers
#                                    with multiple output modes
#   * Unlike consola — zap is service-focused (JSON throughput),
#                       consola is developer-console-focused (UX)
#   * Closest cross-language analogs:
#         * Rust: tracing (tokio-rs/tracing) — similar structured-
#                  event model with subscribers
#         * TS-Node: pino (pino-io/pino) — JSON-only fast logger
#                     for backend services; consola is for CLIs
#         * Python: structlog — typed structured logging
#     zap is the FIRST documented Go logger opening Axis 9
#     (UNIFIED LOGGING / OBSERVABILITY) for the Go language slot.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
